{"ts": "2026-06-21T08:20:27.862", "level": "INFO", "event": "llm_response", "stage": "stage4_narrate", "model": "physics-solver-llm", "elapsed_ms": 12370, "attempt": 1, "response_chars": 1375, "prompt_tokens": 1211, "completion_tokens": 455, "total_tokens": 1666, "response_preview": "1. The problem involves finding the electrostatic force between two point charges in vacuum. We use Coulomb's Law, which states that the force \\( F \\) between two point charges is given by:\n   \\[\n   F = \\frac{q_1 q_2}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0 r^2}\n   \\]\n   This equation directly relates the force to the charges and distance, making it the correct choice for this problem.\n\n2. The values provided are: \\( q_1 = 2 \\mu C = 2 \\times 10^{-6} C \\), \\( q_2 = 3 \\mu C = 3 \\times 10^{-6} C \\), and \\( r = 0.5 m \\).\n\n3. Substituting these values into the equation, we get:\n   \\[\n   F = \\frac{(2 \\times 10^{-6})(3 \\times 10^{-6})}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0 (0.5)^2}\n   \\]\n   Simplifying this expression gives us:\n   \\[\n   F = \\frac{6 \\times 10^{-12}}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0 \\cdot 0.25} = \\frac{6 \\times 10^{-12}}{\\pi \\epsilon_0}\n   \\]\n   The exact value is:\n   \\[\n   F = \\frac{300000000000000000}{1390783067744200033} N\n   \\]\n\n4. Converting this to a decimal, we get:\n   \\[\n   F = 0.215706 \\text{ N}\n   \\]\n\n5. The decision log shows th"}
