{"ts": "2026-06-21T08:20:49.305", "level": "INFO", "event": "llm_response", "stage": "stage4_narrate", "model": "physics-solver-llm", "elapsed_ms": 8673, "attempt": 1, "response_chars": 1305, "prompt_tokens": 943, "completion_tokens": 326, "total_tokens": 1269, "response_preview": "1. The problem involves finding the acceleration of a 5 kg object experiencing a net force of 20 N. We start with Newton's Second Law of Motion, which states that the net force acting on an object is equal to the mass of the object multiplied by its acceleration: \\( F = m \\cdot a \\).\n   - **Why this equation?** This law directly relates the net force (\\(F\\)) to the mass (\\(m\\)) and acceleration (\\(a\\)), making it perfect for solving problems where we need to find one of these quantities given the others.\n\n2. We are solving for \\(a\\) (acceleration). Rearranging the equation, we get: \n   \\[\n   a = \\frac{F}{m}\n   \\]\n   - **Substituted values:** Plugging in the given values, we have:\n     \\[\n     a = \\frac{20 \\text{ N}}{5 \\text{ kg}}\n     \\]\n\n3. Performing the division gives us:\n   \\[\n   a = 4 \\text{ m/s}^2\n   \\]\n   - **Result:** The acceleration of the object is \\(4 \\text{ m/s}^2\\).\n\nThis calculation confirms our choice of using Newton's Second Law, as it directly provides the required re"}
